  "context_summary": "28-year-old woman presents with right ear pain and itching that started two days after a weekend of swimming at a lake. She describes the pain as worse when she puts in an earbud or lies on that side. No fever, no upper respiratory symptoms. The doctor has not yet examined the ear and is deciding whether this is otitis externa versus otitis media before choosing topical versus oral therapy.",
  "good_next_question": "Does it hurt when I gently pull on your outer ear or press on this little bump right in front of your ear canal?",
  "rationale": "Tragal and pinna tenderness is the key bedside maneuver that separates otitis externa from acute otitis media, because OE is an infection of the skin lining the external canal, so any manipulation of the outer ear or canal opening directly reproduces pain; in AOM the pathology is deep to an intact eardrum, so pulling the pinna or pressing the tragus typically does not worsen symptoms. Recent water exposure is a supportive risk factor for OE but isn't diagnostic on its own, since AOM can also follow swimming-related congestion or occur independently. Asking this as a direct, in-the-moment question during exam is more discriminating than asking about pain quality or itching alone, and it changes management immediately: positive tragal tenderness points to topical antibiotic/steroid drops for OE, while a normal pinna-pull exam with a bulging TM would instead point toward oral antibiotics for AOM.",
